## Technical Integration Strategy

Integrating this into your MERN stack (MongoDB, Express, React, Node) involves three core phases.

### Phase 1: Backend Setup
We must create an isolated AI engine in the Node.js backend so API keys remain secure.
1. **SDK Installation:** Run `npm install @google/generative-ai` in `caresync-backend`.
2. **AI Controller:** We create a dedicated file: `caresync-backend/controllers/aiController.js`. This will house two primary functions:
   - `handlePatientChat`: Takes conversational arrays securely and returns symptom triage.
   - `analyzeLabReport`: Triggered alongside `uploadRoutes.js`. It takes the Mulberry local `/uploads/` file stream and pushes it to the AI for medical data extraction.
3. **AI Routes:** Expose `POST /api/ai/chat` and `POST /api/ai/analyze` inside `server.js`.

### Phase 2: Database Enhancements
We need to slightly tweak your Mongoose schemas to safely store what the AI produces.
- **Lab Reports Map:** If you eventually add a `Report` schema, it will include an `aiSummary` string field to cache the AI's explanation so we don't query the API twice for the same report.

### Phase 3: Frontend Deployment (React)
1. **CareSync Bot Component:** Build an isolated, floating `AIChatbot.jsx` component that can be dropped into `PatientDashboard.jsx`. It will feature a slick, distinct UI (perhaps using a gradient aesthetic) to differentiate it from human chat.
2. **Lab Upload Hook:** Inside `LabDashboard.jsx`, the "Upload & Notify" button will display an "AI Analyzing..." loading spinner while the backend reads the PDF.

---

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **HIPAA & Data Privacy**
> Because this is a healthcare platform, sending raw Patient Names or SSNs/National IDs to third-party APIs can violate privacy compliances depending on the region. When sending data from Node.js to the AI Agent, we will strip Personal Identifiable Information (PII) and only send anonymous symptom objects or randomized report chunks.

